EPISTLE ΙΙ.

This epistle is addressed to Lollius Maximus, probably the elder son of M. Lollius, to whom Canu. Iv. 9 was afterwards addressed. The date of the Epistle is not certain. The eighteenth epistle of this book is also addressed to the same Lollius, and we learn from that (v. 55) that he had served under Augustus in the Cantabrian war of B.c. 25—24. It is not improbable that aster serving (as puer) in that war, he returned to Rome, and took up again the practice of declamation, just as Cicero did after his service in the Social War. In that case B.C. ²3 would be a plausible date to assign; but the use of puer in v. 68 is not inconsistent with a date a year or two later. The practice of rhetoric under teachers was often carried on long after the years of manhood had been reached. Cicero was studying under Molo at the age of twenty-eight. The date of Ep. XVIII. is fixed by v. 56 at B.C. 20, and that appears to be certainly later than the present one.
